BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Pediatric Orthopedics and Sports Medicine: The Limping Child
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T200000
DTSTAMP:20260419T063624Z
UID:01ac4c56789411aa@gid-seminars.wnprc.wisc.edu
CATEGORIES:Class/Seminar
DESCRIPTION:Overview\nChildren may develop a limp for a variety of reasons
 \, with causes that differ widely in urgency and management. This lecture 
 provides clinicians with practical strategies to evaluate pediatric limpin
 g through a review of epidemiology\, clinical presentation\, physical exam
 ination\, and diagnostic testing. Learners will explore common infectious 
 and non-infectious causes\, as well as less frequent but critical diagnose
 s\, to improve clinical decision-making and timely management in pediatric
  patients.\n\nRegistration\nRegistration is required.\nAll practitioners: 
 free.\n\nCredits\nAMA PRA Category 1 Credits™ (1.00 hours)\, BOC Categor
 y A Hours/CEUs (1.00 hours)\, Non-Physician Participation Credit (1.00 hou
 rs)\, Occupational Therapy Contact Hours (1.00 hours)\, Physical Therapy C
 ontact Hours (1.00 hours)\n\nTarget Audience\nSpecialties - Orthopedics & 
 Sports Medicine\nProfessions - Athletic Trainer\, Fellow/Resident\, Non-Ph
 ysician\, Occupational Therapist\, Physical Therapist\, Physician\n\nObjec
 tives\nAt the conclusion of this activity\, learners should be able to:\n\
 n1. Define a limp and differentiate common gait patterns in pediatric pati
 ents.  \n2. Identify common infectious causes of limping in children and s
 elect appropriate examination and treatment strategies. \n3. Review common
  non-infectious causes of limping in children and determine appropriate di
 agnostic and management strategies.\n4. Discuss uncommon but clinically si
 gnificant causes of pediatric limping.\n\nAccreditation\nIn support of imp
 roving patient care\, Stanford Medicine is jointly accredited by the Accre
 ditation Council for Continuing Medical Education (ACCME)\, the Accreditat
 ion Council for Pharmacy Education (ACPE)\, and the American Nurses Creden
 tialing Center (ANCC)\, to provide continuing education for the healthcare
  team. \n \nCredit Designation \nAmerican Medical Association (AMA) \nStan
 ford Medicine designates this Live Activity for a maximum of 1.00 AMA PRA 
 Category 1 CreditsTM.  Physicians should claim only the credit \n\nEvent U
 RL: https://events.stanford.edu/event/pediatric-orthopedics-and-sports-med
 icine-the-limping-child\n\nSource: stanford_virtual
LOCATION:Online
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/pediatric-orthopedics-and-sports-med
 icine-the-limping-child
BEGIN:VALARM
ACTION:DISPLAY
DESCRIPTION:Reminder: Pediatric Orthopedics and Sports Medicine: The Limpi
 ng Child
TRIGGER:-PT1H
END:VALARM
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:"When Health Systems Are Under Pressure: Rethinking Health Innovat
 ion from Africa" - Dr. Cherise Dunn
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T200000
DTSTAMP:20260419T063624Z
UID:f239c5eed5907a17@gid-seminars.wnprc.wisc.edu
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk
DESCRIPTION:Session Description:\n\nAcross Africa\, many health systems ar
 e carrying immense pressure while trying to do more with too little: too f
 ew healthcare workers\, constrained budgets\, and major gaps in access to 
 timely care. In that kind of environment\, innovation has to mean more tha
 n novelty. It has to make care more practical\, more reachable\, and more 
 responsive to the realities people face.\n\nIn this talk\, Dr. Dunn reflec
 ts on what it means to rethink innovation from Africa\, especially at a mo
 ment when AI is reshaping healthcare conversations worldwide. At the heart
  of this talk is the idea that Africa should not only be seen as a site of
  need\, but also as a source of insight. She will explore the kinds of sol
 utions these settings call for\, and why perspectives from African health 
 systems matter far beyond the continent.\n\nRSVP to Attend\n\nSpeaker Bio:
 \n\n Dr. Cherise Dunn is a South African health technology entrepreneur\, 
 strategist\, and systems builder working at the intersection of healthcare
 \, advanced manufacturing\, and artificial intelligence. She brings over a
  decade of experience designing and implementing innovation-led programs a
 cross Africa\, the United States\, and Brazil\, with a focus on translatin
 g emerging technologies into practical\, scalable solutions that improve a
 ccess and outcomes. \n\nCherise holds a PhD in Medical Biochemistry and re
 cently completed her Master of Public Health in Health Management at the H
 arvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health. Her work has spanned public heal
 th systems\, venture development\, and workforce innovation\, including le
 ading national-scale training programs reaching over 20\,000 learners and 
 advising on global health and innovation initiatives through platforms suc
 h as the G20\, BRICS\, and the U.S. State Department. \n\nShe is the co-fo
 under of multiple ventures\, including Impact Mechanica\, a U.S.-based com
 pany developing custom\, data-driven protective headgear to reduce traumat
 ic brain injuries\, and Authentica.ai\, an AI-enabled pla\n\nEvent URL: ht
 tps://events.stanford.edu/event/when-health-systems-are-under-pressure-ret
 hinking-health-innovation-from-africa-dr-cherise-dunn\n\nSource: stanford_
 virtual
LOCATION:Online
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/when-health-systems-are-under-pressu
 re-rethinking-health-innovation-from-africa-dr-cherise-dunn
BEGIN:VALARM
ACTION:DISPLAY
DESCRIPTION:Reminder: "When Health Systems Are Under Pressure: Rethinking 
 Health Innovation from Africa" - Dr. Cherise Dunn
TRIGGER:-PT1H
END:VALARM
END:VEVENT
