SUMMARY:CFAR Seminar with Dr. Brooke Nichols - May 7\, 2026
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260507T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260507T173000
DTSTAMP:20260419T063624Z
UID:d9da2ae1ae9320c8@gid-seminars.wnprc.wisc.edu
CATEGORIES:Fred Hutch Center for AIDS Research (CFAR)
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nOnline Meeting Link: https:/
 /washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/h92B3kzpRjy3zxG0GFjrXw\nAccessibility
  Contact: cfar@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Lectures/Seminars\n\nREGISTER NOW!\nRe
 gister via this link for virtual attendance\nzoom registration: \nhttps://
 washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/h92B3kzpRjy3zxG0GFjrXw\n--------------
 ------------------------------------------------------------------\n9:30am
 -10:30am\n*Please note that this Seminar will be taking place earlier in t
 he day than usual in order to accommodate our speaker who will be joining 
 us from a different time zone*\nVIRTUAL\nCFAR Seminar Speaker: Brooke Nich
 ols\nTalk Title: Complexity in the Right Places: Reorienting HIV Models fo
 r Implementation\nBio: \nBrooke Nichols\, PhD\, MSc\, is an Associate Prof
 essor of Global Health at Boston University School of Public Health and an
  infectious disease mathematical modeller and health economist based. Her 
 research sits at the intersection of transmission dynamics\, implementatio
 n modelling\, and health economics\, using quantitative approaches to answ
 er practical questions about how HIV\, tuberculosis\, antimicrobial resist
 ance\, and other pathogens can be tackled more effectively in real-world h
 ealth systems. Her work has shaped national and global health policy acros
 s several domains\, including WHO Target Product Profiles for diagnostics\
 , normative guidance on HIV prevention and care\, and global strategies fo
 r optimal diagnostic use during the COVID-19 pandemic.\n \n\n9:00am-9:30am
 \nVIRTUAL\nNew Faces Speaker: Khai Hoan Tram\nTalk Title: Modeling the Fal
 lout: Projecting the Global Impact of US Funding Cuts\nBio: \nDr. Tram\, M
 D\, MS\, is an infectious diseases physician-scientist in the Division of 
 Allergy & Infectious Diseases at the University of Washington. He conducts
  research on HIV and TB and practices medicine at Harborview Medical Cente
 r and UW Medical Center. He sees patients weekly at the Madison HIV Clinic
 . Dr. Tram attended Stanford University medical schoo\n\nEvent URL: https:
 //washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/h92B3kzpRjy3zxG0GFjrXw\n\nSource: uw
 _cfar
LOCATION:Zoom
URL:https://washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/h92B3kzpRjy3zxG0GFjrXw
